To add a black background specifically to the `<select>` element within your styled component, you need to modify the CSS for that element in your `Wrapper` styled component. From what you've described and the code provided, if you want the `<select>` to have a solid black background (ignoring the gradients you've previously applied to it and other elements), you can do so by directly setting the `background` property of the `.sort-selection--style` class which is being applied to your `<select>` element.

Here's how you can modify the `.sort-selection--style` to have a black background:

```javascript
.sort-selection .sort-selection--style {
  padding: 0.4rem;
  cursor: pointer;
  font-size: 14px;
  color: white; /* This makes the text color white for contrast against the black background */
  background: black; /* Setting the background to black */

  // Remove or comment out the gradient styles if you no longer need them
  // background: #833ab4; 
  // background: -webkit-linear-gradient(to bottom, #fcb045, #fd1d1d, #833ab4);
  // background: linear-gradient(to bottom, #fcb045, #fd1d1d, #833ab4);  
  // background-size: 400%;
  // background-position: 0% 0%;
}
```

In this modification, the background of the `<select>` element styled by the class `.sort-selection--style` is set to black. Additionally, I've set the `color` to white to ensure the text is easily readable against the dark background. You can adjust the `color` property as needed to match your design requirements.

### Note on Gradients and Browser Support
In your original code, you're using gradients on your elements, which is a great way to add depth and visual interest to your design. However, when setting a solid background color like black, simply use `background: black;` as shown above. If you still want to have some elements with gradients and others with solid colors in the same component, just apply the styles selectively as needed.

### Ensuring Browser Compatibility
The CSS changes made here are widely supported in all modern web browsers. However, if you're using advanced CSS features elsewhere in your project or need to support a wide range of browsers, including older versions, it's always a good idea to check for compatibility and consider using vendor prefixes or fallbacks where necessary. For simple changes like setting a background color to black, compatibility concerns are minimal.

Setting a black background for the dropdown portion of a `<select>` element (i.e., the options list that appears when you click the select) is a bit more complex due to the way browsers handle styling of form elements. Form elements like `<select>` are rendered by the operating system rather than the browser, which means their styling options are limited and can vary significantly between browsers and operating systems.

Unfortunately, there's no straightforward, cross-browser compatible way to style the dropdown part of a `<select>` element directly with CSS. Basic styling like background and font color of the select itself can be done easily, but styling the dropdown list options is more restrictive.

That said, here are a few approaches you might consider:

### 1. Use Custom JavaScript-Based Dropdowns
Many UI libraries offer customizable select components which are built from more basic HTML elements that can be styled freely. These components are often designed to mimic the behavior of native select dropdowns but allow for more extensive styling since they're constructed from divs, spans, etc.

For example, libraries like [Select2](https://select2.org/), [Chosen](https://harvesthq.github.io/chosen/), and [React Select](https://react-select.com/home) offer rich options for customization including the ability to style the dropdown portion extensively.

If you're using React, `React Select` is widely used and could be a good choice:

```jsx
import Select from 'react-select';

const options = [
  { value: 'lowest', label: 'Price(lowest)' },
  { value: 'highest', label: 'Price(highest)' },
  { value: 'a-z', label: 'Name(a-z)' },
  { value: 'z-a', label: 'Name(z-a)' },
];

const customStyles = {
  control: (provided, state) => ({
    ...provided,
    background: 'black',
    color: 'white',
  }),
  menu: (provided, state) => ({
    ...provided,
    background: 'black',
  }),
  option: (provided, state) => ({
    ...provided,
    background: state.isSelected ? 'grey' : 'black',
    color: 'white',
  }),
  singleValue: (provided, state) => ({
    ...provided,
    color: 'white',
  }),
};

<Select options={options} styles={customStyles} />
```

### 2. CSS Pseudo-Elements (Limited Support)
Some browsers allow for minimal styling of the dropdown arrow using pseudo-elements, but this does not extend to the dropdown list itself.

```css
select {
  appearance: none; /* Remove default styling */
  background-color: black;
  color: white;
}

/* This only works in some browsers and doesn't style the dropdown list */
select::-ms-expand {
  background: black;
  color: white;
}
```

### 3. Creating a Completely Custom Dropdown
You can build your own dropdown control using a combination of HTML elements like `div` and `ul`/`li`, showing and hiding the list on click with JavaScript or CSS. This approach gives you full control over the styling at the cost of having to implement some functionality (like keyboard navigation) from scratch.

In summary, for full control over the styling of both the select box and its dropdown list across all browsers, using a custom JavaScript-based component is the most reliable option. This does mean adding a potentially significant amount of JavaScript to your page, so it's worth considering the trade-offs for your specific use case.

